&lt;h1 id=&#34;ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)&#34; class=&#34;active&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34;  href=&#34;#ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ARP is not a pure layer-3 protocol, nor a pure layer-2 protocol. It generally works at layer 2 by using layer 3 IP address information&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ARP works in conjunction with IPv4 to discover the MAC address of a host or node on the local network&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;And to maintain a database that maps IP addresses to MAC addresses on the local network&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ARP is a Layer 2 protocol that uses Layer 3â€™s IP address information&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It operates only within its local network&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ARP relies on broadcasting&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;2&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ARP Table&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ARP tableâ€”The database of IP-to-MAC address mappings&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;An ARP table can contain two types of entries:&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Dynamicâ€”Created when a client makes an ARP request that could not be satisfied by data already in the ARP table&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Staticâ€”Those someone entered manually using the ARP utility (arp command)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Check ARP table&lt;ul&gt;
